What would be Indonesia’s most precious assets in the next 100 years? Indonesia and its people speak a lot of languages. This linguistic richness can be Indonesia’s most precious asset in the next century. Hopefully and through national unification, the richness of the languages can lead Indonesia to appreciate its diversity to lead to even more unity, rather than fragment the unity into disunity.

Last but not least, Indonesia would be best off if democratic and constitutional values were internalized in Indonesian culture. In the last century Indonesia experienced democratic and constitutional values to fulfill the principle of ‘good governance’ and to uphold the rule of law. Indonesia in the next century should become a country of the law. As Adnan Buyung Nasution once put it, ‘be a country of the law, not of men.’

Dr. Arief Rachman’s essay writer has been teaching in Yayasan Pendidikan Darma Wacana (YPDW), Indonesian Center for International Studies (ICES) Yogyakarta, University of Indonesia, Universitas Trisakti Jakarta, Universitas Padjajaran Bandung. He is also a free lance writer and researcher. He is married to Dian Furwati and has 3 daughters. He can be reached at arifrizki@burhanuddin.co.id.
